{{Expert-subject|U.S. Supreme Court cases|date=October 2008}} {{Infobox SCOTUS case |Litigants=Mississippi v. Johnson |ArgueDate=April 12 |ArgueYear=1867 |DecideDate=April 15 |DecideYear=1867 |FullName=The State of Mississippi v. Andrew Johnson, President of the United States |USVol=71 |USPage=475 |ParallelCitations=4 [[John William Wallace|Wall.]] 475; 18 [[L. Ed.]] 437 |Prior= |Subsequent= |Holding=In the course of his enforcement of the Reconstruction Acts, President Johnson was necessarily exercising discretion and so could not be sued. |SCOTUS=1865-1867 |Majority=Chase |JoinMajority=''unanimous'' |Concurrence= |JoinConcurrence= |Concurrence2= |JoinConcurrence2= |Concurrence/Dissent= |JoinConcurrence/Dissent= |Dissent= |JoinDissent= |Dissent2= |JoinDissent2= |LawsApplied= }} '''''Mississippi v. Johnson''''', 71 U.S. (4 Wall.) 475 (1867), was the first suit to be brought against a [[President of the United States]] in the [[Supreme Court of the United States|United States Supreme Court]]. The state of [[Mississippi]] attempted to sue President [[Andrew Johnson]] for enforcing [[Reconstruction era of the United States|Reconstruction]]. The court decided, based on a previous decision of ''[[Marbury v. Madison]]'' that the President has two kinds of task: ministerial and discretionary. Discretionary tasks are ones the president can choose to do or not to do, while ministerial tasks are ones required by his office: those whose failure to perform could leave him in violation of the [[United States Constitution|Constitution]]. The court ruled that by enforcing Reconstruction, Johnson was acting in an "executive and political" capacity&mdash;a discretionary rather than a ministerial one&mdash;and so he could not be sued.
